Identifiers
===========


 @{" database-ref " Link "database-ref"} 
 @{" table-ref " Link "table-ref"} 
 @{" column-ref " Link "column-ref"} 
 @{" table-alias-ref " Link "table-alias-ref"} 
 @{" column-alias-ref " Link "column-alias-ref"} 
 @{" cursor-ref " Link "cursor-ref"} 
 @{" index-ref " Link "index-ref"} 


@EndNode

@Node "database-ref" "sqlrefman.guide/database-ref"
@Next "table-ref"
@Prev "Identifiers"
@Toc "Identifiers"

database-ref
------------

A database-ref is composed of a letter followed by zero or more
characters from the set of numbers, letters, '_', '#'.  Thus, A#_o1ne
is a legal database-ref, while _a#45 is not.

An database-ref cannot be a valid SQL keyword.


@EndNode

@Node "table-ref" "sqlrefman.guide/table-ref"
@Next "column-ref"
@Prev "database-ref"
@Toc "Identifiers"

table-ref
---------

A table-ref is composed of a letter followed by zero or more characters
from the set of numbers, letters, '_', '#'.  Thus, A#_o1ne is a legal
table-ref, while _a#45 is not.

A table-ref cannot be a valid SQL keyword.


@EndNode

@Node "column-ref" "sqlrefman.guide/column-ref"
@Next "table-alias-ref"
@Prev "table-ref"
@Toc "Identifiers"

column-ref
----------

A column-ref is composed of a letter followed by zero or more characters
from the set of numbers, letters, '_', '#'.  Thus, A#_o1ne is a legal
column-ref, while _a#45 is not.

A column-ref cannot be a valid SQL keyword.


@EndNode

@Node "table-alias-ref" "sqlrefman.guide/table-alias-ref"
@Next "column-alias-ref"
@Prev "column-ref"
@Toc "Identifiers"

table-alias-ref
---------------

A table-alias-ref is composed of a letter followed by zero or more
characters from the set of numbers, letters, '_', '#'.  Thus, A#_o1ne
is a legal table-alias-ref, while _a#45 is not.

A table-alias-ref cannot be a valid SQL keyword.


@EndNode

@Node "column-alias-ref" "sqlrefman.guide/column-alias-ref"
@Next "cursor-ref"
@Prev "table-alias-ref"
@Toc "Identifiers"

column-alias-ref
----------------

A column-alias-ref is composed of a letter followed by zero or more
characters from the set of numbers, letters, '_', '#'.  Thus, A#_o1ne
is a legal column-alias-ref, while _a#45 is not.

A column-alias-ref cannot be a valid SQL keyword.


@EndNode

@Node "cursor-ref" "sqlrefman.guide/cursor-ref"
@Next "index-ref"
@Prev "column-alias-ref"
@Toc "Identifiers"

cursor-ref
----------

A cursor-ref is composed of a letter followed by zero or more characters
from the set of numbers, letters, '_', '#'.  Thus, A#_o1ne is a legal
cursor-ref, while _a#45 is not.

A cursor-ref cannot be a valid SQL keyword.


@EndNode

@Node "index-ref" "sqlrefman.guide/index-ref"
@Next "Literals"
@Prev "cursor-ref"
@Toc "Identifiers"

index-ref
---------

An index-ref is composed of a letter followed by zero or more characters
from the set of numbers, letters, '_', '#'.  Thus, A#_o1ne is a legal
index-ref, while _a#45 is not.

An index-ref cannot be a valid SQL keyword.


@EndNode

@Node "Literals" "sqlrefman.guide/Literals"
@Next "Data Definition"
@Prev "Identifiers"
@Toc "Simple Elements"

Literals
========

This section defines the literals of the various data types available.


 @{" integer " Link "integer"} 		INTEGER and SMALLINT
 @{" float " Link "float"} 		FLOAT
 @{" character " Link "character"} 		CHAR(size)
 @{" date " Link "date"} 		DATE
 @{" time " Link "time"} 		TIME


@EndNode

@Node "integer" "sqlrefman.guide/integer"
@Next "float"
@Prev "Literals"
@Toc "Literals"

integer
-------

An integer literal consists of one or more digits 0 through 9.

45332 is an example of an integer literal.


@EndNode

@Node "float" "sqlrefman.guide/float"
@Next "character"
@Prev "integer"
@Toc "Literals"

float
-----

A float literal consists of an integer literal (see @{"integer" Link "integer"}), a period
(decimal point), and another integer literal.

45.674 is an example of a float literal.  Note that .456 is *not* a
valid float literal.


@EndNode

@Node "character" "sqlrefman.guide/character"
@Next "date"
@Prev "float"
@Toc "Literals"

character
---------

A character literal consists of a string of characters enclosed in
single quotes (').

'Hello, World' is an example of a character literal.


@EndNode

@Node "date" "sqlrefman.guide/date"
@Next "time"
@Prev "character"
@Toc "Literals"

date
----

A date literal is a character literal (see @{"character" Link "character"}) with a special
format. The format is 'mm/dd/yyyy', where mm is the month (1 is
January, 12 is December), dd is the day of the month, and yyyy is the
year.

'4/21/1993' is an example of a date literal.


@EndNode

@Node "time" "sqlrefman.guide/time"
@Next "Data Definition"
@Prev "date"
@Toc "Literals"

time
----

A time literal is a character literal (see @{"character" Link "character"}) with a special
format.  The format is 'hh:mm:ss', where hh is the hour (00 is
midnight, 23 is 11pm), mm is minute (00-59), and ss is the second
(00-59).

'17:35:01' is an example of a time literal.


@EndNode

@Node "Data Definition" "sqlrefman.guide/Data Definition"
@Next "Data IO"
