Data Definition
***************


 @{" CREATE DATABASE " Link "CREATE DATABASE"} 
 @{" CREATE TABLE " Link "CREATE TABLE"} 
 @{" DROP TABLE " Link "DROP TABLE"} 
 @{" CREATE INDEX " Link "CREATE INDEX"} 
 @{" DROP INDEX " Link "DROP INDEX"} 


@EndNode

@Node "CREATE DATABASE" "sqlrefman.guide/CREATE DATABASE"
@Next "CREATE TABLE"
@Prev "Data Definition"
@Toc "Data Definition"

CREATE DATABASE
===============

`CREATE DATABASE' DATABASE-REF

Creates and opens specified database.  A database consists of a group of
tables and global information that applies to those tables.  This
command will fail if a database is already open.

See @{"database-ref" Link "database-ref"}.


@EndNode

@Node "CREATE TABLE" "sqlrefman.guide/CREATE TABLE"
@Next "DROP TABLE"
@Prev "CREATE DATABASE"
@Toc "Data Definition"

CREATE TABLE
============

`CREATE TABLE' TABLE-REF `(' TABLE-DEF-ITEM-LIST `)'

This statement will create the specified table.  If a table already
exists, it will be overwritten.  However, you cannot create a table is
currently open.  The table will be automatically opened after creation.
 You must have an open database (see @{"CREATE DATABASE" Link "CREATE DATABASE"} or see
@{"OPEN DATABASE" Link "OPEN DATABASE"}), or this command will fail.

See @{"table-ref" Link "table-ref"}. See @{"table-def-item" Link "table-def-item"}.


@EndNode

@Node "DROP TABLE" "sqlrefman.guide/DROP TABLE"
@Next "CREATE INDEX"
@Prev "CREATE TABLE"
@Toc "Data Definition"

DROP TABLE
==========

`DROP TABLE' TABLE-REF

This statement will delete the specified table and remove it from the
database.  The table must be currently open.

See @{"table-ref" Link "table-ref"}.


@EndNode

@Node "CREATE INDEX" "sqlrefman.guide/CREATE INDEX"
@Next "DROP INDEX"
@Prev "DROP TABLE"
@Toc "Data Definition"

CREATE INDEX
============

`CREATE INDEX' INDEX-REF `ON' TABLE-REF `(' ORDER-REF-LIST `)'

This statement will create an index on the specified open table.  If
the table contains any rows, they will be entered into the index. 
Likewise, all new rows will be entered.  All index entries must be
unique.  If any existing rows contain non-unique entries for the index,
the command will fail.

See @{"index-ref" Link "index-ref"}. See @{"table-ref" Link "table-ref"}. See @{"order-ref" Link "order-ref"}.


@EndNode

@Node "DROP INDEX" "sqlrefman.guide/DROP INDEX"
@Next "Data IO"
@Prev "CREATE INDEX"
@Toc "Data Definition"

DROP INDEX
==========

`DROP INDEX' INDEX-REF `ON' TABLE-REF

This statement will delete the specified index from the specified open
table.

See @{"index-ref" Link "index-ref"}. See @{"table-ref" Link "table-ref"}.


@EndNode

@Node "Data IO" "sqlrefman.guide/Data IO"
@Next "Data Manipulation"
@Prev "Data Definition"
@Toc "Main"

Data IO
*******


 @{" OPEN DATABASE " Link "OPEN DATABASE"} 
 @{" CLOSE DATABASE " Link "CLOSE DATABASE"} 
 @{" OPEN TABLE " Link "OPEN TABLE"} 
 @{" CLOSE TABLE " Link "CLOSE TABLE"} 


@EndNode

@Node "OPEN DATABASE" "sqlrefman.guide/OPEN DATABASE"
@Next "CLOSE DATABASE"
@Prev "Data IO"
@Toc "Data IO"

OPEN DATABASE
=============

`OPEN DATABASE' DATABASE-REF

Opens specified database.  Any tables that are created will be added to
the currently open database.  This command will fail if a database is
already open.


@EndNode

@Node "CLOSE DATABASE" "sqlrefman.guide/CLOSE DATABASE"
@Next "OPEN TABLE"
@Prev "OPEN DATABASE"
@Toc "Data IO"

CLOSE DATABASE
==============

`CLOSE DATABASE'

Closes the currently open database.


@EndNode

@Node "OPEN TABLE" "sqlrefman.guide/OPEN TABLE"
@Next "CLOSE TABLE"
@Prev "CLOSE DATABASE"
@Toc "Data IO"

OPEN TABLE
==========

`OPEN TABLE' TABLE-REF

This statement will open the specified table.  The must have been
previously created, or this command will fail.


@EndNode

@Node "CLOSE TABLE" "sqlrefman.guide/CLOSE TABLE"
@Next "Data Manipulation"
@Prev "OPEN TABLE"
@Toc "Data IO"

CLOSE TABLE
===========

`CLOSE TABLE' TABLE

This statement will close the specified table.  All non-system (ie user)
tables must be closed before you may exit SQLdb.


@EndNode

@Node "Data Manipulation" "sqlrefman.guide/Data Manipulation"
@Next "Misc"
@Prev "Data IO"
@Toc "Main"

Data Manipulation
*****************


 @{" query-spec " Link "query-spec"} 		SELECT statement
 @{" insert-spec " Link "insert-spec"} 		INSERT statement
 @{" delete-spec " Link "delete-spec"} 		DELETE statement
 @{" update-spec " Link "update-spec"} 		UPDATE statement
 @{" Cursors " Link "Cursors"} 
 @{" Importing " Link "Importing"} 


@EndNode

@Node "query-spec" "sqlrefman.guide/query-spec"
@Next "insert-spec"
@Prev "Data Manipulation"
@Toc "Data Manipulation"

query-spec
==========

QUERY-SPEC:
        `SELECT' [ `DISTINCT' ] { SELECT-ITEM-LIST | `*' }
           `FROM' BASETABLE-REF-LIST
         [ `WHERE' SEARCH-CONDITION ]
         [ `GROUP BY' GROUP-REF-LIST
         [ `HAVING' SEARCH-CONDITION ] ]
         [ `ORDER BY' ORDER-REF-LIST ]
         [ `OUTPUT TO' FILE-NAME ]

This statement is used to retrieve information from the database.  It is
made up of several clauses, which are explained in the following
sections.

If `DISTINCT' is specified, then all duplicate rows will be removed
from the result table.

The clauses are, in general, order sensitive.  For example, the `OUTPUT
TO' clause should always be the last clause in the `SELECT' statement.


 @{" FROM " Link "FROM"} 
 @{" WHERE " Link "WHERE"} 
 @{" GROUP BY " Link "GROUP BY"} 
 @{" HAVING " Link "HAVING"} 
 @{" ORDER BY " Link "ORDER BY"} 
 @{" OUTPUT TO " Link "OUTPUT TO"} 


@EndNode

@Node "FROM" "sqlrefman.guide/FROM"
@Next "WHERE"
@Prev "query-spec"
@Toc "query-spec"

FROM
----

This clause specifies which tables SQLdb is supposed to gather
information from.  Conceptually, SQLdb will generate a cartesian
product of all the specfied tables.

See @{"basetable-ref" Link "basetable-ref"}.


@EndNode

@Node "WHERE" "sqlrefman.guide/WHERE"
@Next "GROUP BY"
@Prev "FROM"
@Toc "query-spec"

WHERE
-----

This clause is used by several other statements, and is used to restrict
the set of rows to be operated on.  Let T be the result of the
immediately preceding `FROM' clause.  The result of the `WHERE' clause
is a table that is derived from T by eliminating all rows for which the
SEARCH-CONDITION does not evaluate to TRUE.

See @{"search-condition" Link "search-condition"}.


@EndNode

@Node "GROUP BY" "sqlrefman.guide/GROUP BY"
@Next "HAVING"
@Prev "WHERE"
@Toc "query-spec"

GROUP BY
--------

Let T be the result of the `FROM' clause and `WHERE' clause (if any). 
Each "column" mentioned in the `GROUP BY' clause must be a column of T.
 The result of the `GROUP BY' clause is a set of tables, derived from T
by conceptually rearranging it into the minimum number of groups such
that within any one group all rows have the same value for the
combination of columns identified by the `GROUP BY' clause.

See @{"group-ref" Link "group-ref"}.


@EndNode

@Node "HAVING" "sqlrefman.guide/HAVING"
@Next "ORDER BY"
@Prev "GROUP BY"
@Toc "query-spec"

HAVING
------

Let G be the grouped table result from the evaluation of the
immediately preceding `FROM' clause, `WHERE' clause (if any), and
`GROUP BY' clause.  The result of the `HAVING' clause are those groups
for which the SEARCH-CONDITION is TRUE.

See @{"search-condition" Link "search-condition"}.


@EndNode

@Node "ORDER BY" "sqlrefman.guide/ORDER BY"
@Next "OUTPUT TO"
@Prev "HAVING"
@Toc "query-spec"

ORDER BY
--------

This clause orders the result of the preceding clauses, including the
projection of the SELECT-ITEM-LIST.  The rows are ordered according to
the ORDER-REF-LIST, with each ORDER-REF being a progressively minor
sort key, to break ties of the previous sort key.  All ORDER-REF's must
refer to an item in the SELECT-ITEM-LIST.

See @{"order-ref" Link "order-ref"}. See @{"select-item" Link "select-item"}.


@EndNode

@Node "OUTPUT TO" "sqlrefman.guide/OUTPUT TO"
@Next "insert-spec"
@Prev "ORDER BY"
@Toc "query-spec"

OUTPUT TO
---------

This command will send the normal query output to the specified
filename.


@EndNode

@Node "insert-spec" "sqlrefman.guide/insert-spec"
@Next "delete-spec"
@Prev "query-spec"
@Toc "Data Manipulation"

insert-spec
===========

INSERT-SPEC:
        `INSERT INTO' TABLE-REF
          [ `(' COLUMN-REF-LIST `)' ]
          { `VALUES' `(' INSERT-ITEM-LIST `)' |
            QUERY-SPEC
	  }

This statement is used to put new rows into a table.  If the
COLUMN-REF-LIST is omitted, it is equivalent to specifying all of the
columns of the target table, in left-to-right order.  Any columns not
named will a `NULL' value for each newly inserted row.

If a query is supplied instead of a value list, the query is executed
and all rows in the result will be inserted into the table.

See @{"table-ref" Link "table-ref"}. See @{"column-ref" Link "column-ref"}. See @{"insert-item" Link "insert-item"}. See @{"query-spec" Link "query-spec"}.


@EndNode

@Node "delete-spec" "sqlrefman.guide/delete-spec"
@Next "update-spec"
@Prev "insert-spec"
@Toc "Data Manipulation"

delete-spec
===========

DELETE-SPEC:
        `DELETE FROM' TABLE-REF
          [ `WHERE'
            { SEARCH-CONDITION |
              `CURRENT OF' CURSOR-REF
            }
          ]

This statement is used to delete rows that satisfy the optional WHERE
clause. If the WHERE clause is omitted, all rows in the table are
deleted.  If a cursor is specified, then the row the cursor is on is
deleted.

See @{"table-ref" Link "table-ref"}. See @{"cursor-ref" Link "cursor-ref"}. See @{"search-condition" Link "search-condition"}.


@EndNode

@Node "update-spec" "sqlrefman.guide/update-spec"
@Next "Cursors"
@Prev "delete-spec"
@Toc "Data Manipulation"

update-spec
===========

UPDATE-SPEC:
        `UPDATE' TABLE-REF
            `SET' ASSIGNMENT-LIST
          [ `WHERE' { search-condition |
                            `CURRENT OF' CURSOR-REF
                    }
          ]

This statement is used to modify existing rows that satisfy the
optional WHERE clause.  If the WHERE clause is omitted, all rows in the
table are modified.

See @{"table-ref" Link "table-ref"}. See @{"cursor-ref" Link "cursor-ref"}. See @{"assignment" Link "assignment"}. See @{"search-condition" Link "search-condition"}.


@EndNode

@Node "Cursors" "sqlrefman.guide/Cursors"
@Next "Importing"
@Prev "update-spec"
@Toc "Data Manipulation"

Cursors
=======

The following statements can be type interactively, but they are
intended to be used through an ARexx port.


 @{" DECLARE " Link "DECLARE"} 		Declaring a cursor
 @{" OPEN " Link "OPEN"} 		Open a cursor
 @{" FETCH " Link "FETCH"} 		Fetch a row through a cursor
 @{" CLOSE " Link "CLOSE"} 		Closing a cusor


@EndNode

@Node "DECLARE" "sqlrefman.guide/DECLARE"
@Next "OPEN"
@Prev "Cursors"
@Toc "Cursors"

DECLARE
-------

`DECLARE' CURSOR-REF `CURSOR FOR' QUERY-SPEC

This statement will create and define a cursor.  The cursor is
positioned before the first row of the result table of the QUERY-SPEC.

See @{"cursor-ref" Link "cursor-ref"}. See @{"query-spec" Link "query-spec"}.


@EndNode

@Node "OPEN" "sqlrefman.guide/OPEN"
@Next "FETCH"
@Prev "DECLARE"
@Toc "Cursors"

OPEN
----

`OPEN' CURSOR-REF

This statement will execute a previously declared cursor's QUERY-SPEC. 
You must close every cursor that is opened.


@EndNode

@Node "FETCH" "sqlrefman.guide/FETCH"
@Next "CLOSE"
@Prev "OPEN"
@Toc "Cursors"

FETCH
-----

`FETCH' { `COLUMNS' | `FIRST' | `LAST' | `PREVIOUS' | `NEXT' |
`ABSOLUTE' INTEGER | `RELATIVE' INTEGER } `OF' CURSOR-REF

This statement will retrieve the specified row or column list, of the
table created by the cursor's QUERY-SPEC.

If a column list is specified, it will return three elements for each
column of the result table separated by a space: COLUMN-REF COLUMN-TYPE
MAXIMUM-VALUE-SIZE

See @{"column-ref" Link "column-ref"}.


@EndNode

@Node "CLOSE" "sqlrefman.guide/CLOSE"
@Next "Misc"
@Prev "FETCH"
@Toc "Cursors"

CLOSE
-----

`CLOSE' CURSOR-REF

This statement will close and remove an existing cursor.  A cursor that
has been closed must be re-declared and re-opened.


@EndNode

@Node "search-condition" "sqlrefman.guide/search-condition"

search-condition
****************

SEARCH-CONDITION:
        SEARCH-ITEM |
        SEARCH-ITEM { `AND' | `OR' }
        SEARCH-ITEM

Each search-item evaluates to a true, false, AMARK, or IMARK.  This is a
four value logic system.

Truth Tables:

AND| F  A  I  T		OR| F  A  I  T
--------------		-------------
 F | F  F  F  F		F | F  A  F  T
 A | F  A  I  A		A | A  A  A  T
 I | F  I  I  I		I | F  A  I  T
 T | F  A  I  T		T | T  T  T  T

See @{"search-item" Link "search-item"}.


@EndNode

@Node "search-item" "sqlrefman.guide/search-item"

search-item
===========

SEARCH-ITEM:
        { SEARCH-TEST |
          { `NOT' | `MAYBE_A' | `MAYBE_I' | `MAYBE' }
          `(' SEARCH-CONDITION `)'
        }

The logical operators NOT, MAYBE_A, MAYBE_I, MAYBE are defined below:

	P |NOT P   P | MAYBE_I P   P | MAYBE_A P   P | MAYBE P
	-------   ------------   ------------   ----------
	t | f	   t | f	   t | f	   t | f
	a | a      a | f           a | t	   a | t
	i | i      i | t 	   i | f	   i | t
  	f | t      f | f 	   f | f	   f | f

See @{"search-test" Link "search-test"}.


@EndNode

@Node "search-test" "sqlrefman.guide/search-test"

search-test
-----------

SEARCH-TEST:
        COMPARISON-TEST | LIKE-TEST |
        SET-TEST | QUANTIFIED-TEST |
        EXISTENCE-TEST | IS-NULL-TEST


 @{" comparison-test " Link "comparison-test"} 
 @{" like-test " Link "like-test"} 
 @{" set-test " Link "set-test"} 
 @{" quantified-test " Link "quantified-test"} 
 @{" existence-test " Link "existence-test"} 
 @{" is-null-test " Link "is-null-test"} 


@EndNode

@Node "comparison-test" "sqlrefman.guide/comparison-test"
@Next "like-test"
@Prev "search-test"
@Toc "search-test"

comparison-test
---------------

COMPARISON-TEST:
        EXPR
        { `=' | `<>' | `<' | `<=' | `>' | `>=' }
        { EXPR | QUERY-SPEC }

In the case of an QUERY-SPEC on the right-hand side, the EXPR is
compared with the first element of the the first row of the result
table.

See @{"query-spec" Link "query-spec"}. See @{"expr" Link "expr"}.


@EndNode

@Node "like-test" "sqlrefman.guide/like-test"
@Next "set-test"
@Prev "comparison-test"
@Toc "search-test"

like-test
---------

LIKE-TEST:
        COLUMN-REF [ `NOT' ] `LIKE'
        STRING-PATTERN
        [ `ESCAPE' CHARSTR ]

A string pattern is a string literal.  The '%' is a wildcard to match 0
or more characters, and the '_' is a wildcard to match one character.
The escape character, if specified, will turn a '%' or '_' into a normal
character.

	Example:  foo LIKE 'ab#%c' ESCAPE '#' will match the string 'ab%c'.

See @{"column-ref" Link "column-ref"}.


@EndNode

@Node "set-test" "sqlrefman.guide/set-test"
@Next "quantified-test"
@Prev "like-test"
@Toc "search-test"

set-test
--------

SET-TEST:
        EXPR [ `NOT' ] `IN'
        { `(' LITERAL-LIST `)' | QUERY-SPEC }

See @{"expr" Link "expr"}. See @{"Literals" Link "Literals"}. See @{"query-spec" Link "query-spec"}.


@EndNode

@Node "quantified-test" "sqlrefman.guide/quantified-test"
@Next "existence-test"
@Prev "set-test"
@Toc "search-test"

quantified-test
---------------

QUANTIFIED-TEST:
        EXPR
        { `=' | `<>' | `<' | `<=' | `>' | `>=' }
        { `ALL' | `ANY' | `SOME' } QUERY-SPEC

See @{"expr" Link "expr"}. See @{"query-spec" Link "query-spec"}.


@EndNode

@Node "existence-test" "sqlrefman.guide/existence-test"
@Next "is-null-test"
@Prev "quantified-test"
@Toc "search-test"

existence-test
--------------

`existence-test':
        [ `NOT' ] `EXISTS' QUERY-SPEC


@EndNode

@Node "is-null-test" "sqlrefman.guide/is-null-test"
@Prev "existence-test"
@Toc "search-test"

is-null-test
------------

`is-null-test':
        `IS' [ `NOT' ] `NULL'


@EndNode

@Node "expr" "sqlrefman.guide/expr"

expr
----

EXPR:
        EXPR-ITEM |
        EXPR-ITEM { `+' | `-' | `*' | `/' } EXPR-ITEM

The four operators have equal precedence.  Use parentheses to force a
particular evaluation order.

See @{"expr-item" Link "expr-item"}.


@EndNode

@Node "expr-item" "sqlrefman.guide/expr-item"

expr-item
---------

EXPR-ITEM:
        FUNCTION | VALUE | COLUMN-REF | `(' EXPR `)'

See @{"function" Link "function"}. See @{"value" Link "value"}. See @{"column-ref" Link "column-ref"}. See @{"expr" Link "expr"}.


@EndNode

@Node "value" "sqlrefman.guide/value"

value
-----

VALUE:
        LITERAL | `AMARK' | `IMARK' | `NULL'

See @{"Literals" Link "Literals"}.


@EndNode

@Node "function" "sqlrefman.guide/function"

function
--------

FUNCTION:
        { `AVG' | `MAX' | `MIN' | `SUM' | `COUNT' } `(' expr `)'

Functions can only be applied to numeric (`FLOAT', `SMALLINT', and
`INTEGER') columns.

	`AVG'		average of all values in an expression
	`MAX'		maximum value in an expression
	`MIN'		minimum value in an expression
	`SUM'		total of values in an expression
	`COUNT'		number of values (rows)


@EndNode

@Node "assignment" "sqlrefman.guide/assignment"

assignment
----------

ASSIGNMENT:
	QUALCOLUMN-REF `=' EXPR

See @{"qualcolumn-ref" Link "qualcolumn-ref"}. See @{"expr" Link "expr"}.


@EndNode

@Node "insert-item" "sqlrefman.guide/insert-item"

insert-item
-----------

INSERT-ITEM:
	VALUE

See @{"value" Link "value"}.


@EndNode

@Node "select-item" "sqlrefman.guide/select-item"

select-item
-----------

SELECT-ITEM:
	EXPR [ `AS' COLUMN-ALIAS-REF ]

Column aliases can be used to reference an expression later in the
select-item-list.

	Example:  SELECT col1,col1 AS foocol, foocol*2 AS bleh FROM footab;

	col1  foocol  bleh
	---  -----  ---
	1     1       2
	3     3       6

See @{"expr" Link "expr"}. See @{"column-alias-ref" Link "column-alias-ref"}.


@EndNode

@Node "basetable-ref" "sqlrefman.guide/basetable-ref"

basetable-ref
-------------

BASETABLE-REF:
	TABLE-REF [ TABLE-ALIAS-REF ]

See @{"table-ref" Link "table-ref"}. See @{"table-alias-ref" Link "table-alias-ref"}.


@EndNode

@Node "qualcolumn-ref" "sqlrefman.guide/qualcolumn-ref"

qualcolumn-ref
--------------

QUALCOLUMN-REF:
	[ { TABLE-REF | TABLE-ALIAS-REF } . ] COLUMN-REF

See @{"table-ref" Link "table-ref"}. See @{"table-alias-ref" Link "table-alias-ref"}. See @{"column-ref" Link "column-ref"}.


@EndNode

@Node "group-ref" "sqlrefman.guide/group-ref"

group-ref
---------

GROUP-REF:
	QUALCOLUMN-REF | INTEGER

See @{"qualcolumn-ref" Link "qualcolumn-ref"}. See @{"integer" Link "integer"}.


@EndNode

@Node "order-ref" "sqlrefman.guide/order-ref"

order-ref
---------

ORDER-REF:
	GROUP-REF [ { `ASC' | `DESC' } ]

See @{"group-ref" Link "group-ref"}.


@EndNode

@Node "table-def-item" "sqlrefman.guide/table-def-item"

table-def-item
--------------

TABLE-DEF-ITEM:
	COLUMN-DEF

See @{"column-def" Link "column-def"}.


@EndNode

@Node "column-def" "sqlrefman.guide/column-def"

column-def
----------

COLUMN-DEF:
	COLUMN-REF
	{ `INTEGER' | `SMALLINT' |
	  `FLOAT' | `CHAR('INTEGER`)' |
	  `DATE' | `TIME'
	}

The maximum size of CHAR column is 1024.

See @{"Literals" Link "Literals"}.


@EndNode

